The 3 granting agencies are the main source of federal funding for research, research training and innovation in Canadian  post-secondary institutions. They include the: 
•   Social Sciences and Humanities Research Council of Canada (SSHRC) 
•   Natural Sciences and Engineering Research Council (NSERC)

Genome Canada and Canada Foundation for Innovation (CFI) are also 2 not-for-profit organizations that support research  and innovation in specific areas. They primarily provide funds for the direct costs of research and research training through  competitive peer-reviewed processes that provide a more-or-less comprehensive coverage of all

age of all areas of R&D activity,  from fundamental to applied research. 
In addition, CFI provides funding for infrastructure at Canadian universities, colleges, research hospitals and not-for-profit  organizations. Other research funding sources such as Genome Canada also play a role in this area. Further information  on these organizations is provided in the table below.

Organizational structure 
The NRC is comprised of 4 integrated R&D divisions and an Industrial Research  Assistance Program (IRAP). Each of the 4 R&D divisions is headed by a vice-president,  which collectively form the NRC’s Senior Executive Committee. Under these divisions,  there are 13 research centres focused on key industry sec

dustry sectors, each guided by an  advisory board. These research centres represent areas of strategic importance and  economic value for Canada. Within each research centre are a variety of programs  focused on addressing specific priorities and challenges through technical and research  services, and research facilities.

Canada’s science, technology and innovation ecosystem  Page 2 
1 Introduction 
Canada has a long history of research excellence and scientific success. The  government continues to build on that foundation through investments in science,  technology and innovation. Canada’s Federal Budget 2024 outlines key ongoing actions  to  boost research, innovation and productivity .  
Canada’s innovation e

novation ecosystem consists of federal government departments and  agencies, not-for-profit organizations supported by federal funding, private sector  businesses, and academic organizations. These players work together to conduct  research and development (R&D), develop innovative products, commercialize and  apply innovations for the betterment of society, and train highly qualified people to  s

ople to  support the advancement of knowledge and economic prosperity in Canada.  
This report provides an overview of the Canadian federal government’s support for  science, technology and innovation, and presents a profile of the National Research  Council of Canada (NRC) and the key federal funding agencies. 
2 Federal government support for 
Canadian science, technology and  innovation 
The Go

on 
The Government of Canada (GC) supports science and technology through federal  science-based departments and agencies that conduct research and development  (R&D), and also through programs to fund research and research infrastructure. In  addition, the federal government participates in international initiatives to access global  knowledge, talent and major research facilities (such as intern

as international science  engagement through the  New Frontiers in Research Fund  that allows emerging  researchers to expand their horizons, work across disciplines and borders). 
There are also tax measures to encourage investment in research and development as  well as marketplace framework policies aimed at creating a competitive environment to  support innovative businesses.

4 The NRC: a science-based department 
and agency 
At a glance 
1. Vision: A better Canada and world through excellence in research and innovation. 
2. Mission: To have an impact by advancing knowledge, applying leading-edge 
technologies, and working with other innovators to find creative, relevant and  sustainable solutions to Cana

ns to Canada's current and future economic, social and  environmental challenges. 
3. The NRC has 3 departmental results for tracking and reporting against its core 
responsibilities: 
a. scientific and technological knowledge advances 
b. innovative businesses grow  
c. evidence-based solutions inform decisions in government priority areas 
Overview 
The National Research Council of Canada (NRC)

ada (NRC) is the Government of Canada's largest  science and research organization.  
It aims to bridge the innovation gap between early-stage research and development  (R&D) and commercialization. To accomplish its mission, the NRC has an annual budget  of $1.5 billion, 4200 staff members including scientists, engineers, technicians and other  specialists (2023-24).  
To support socio-economic be

conomic benefits for Canada, the NRC licenses the intellectual  property (IP) it develops. IP protection tools used by the NRC include patent, copyright,  trademark, official marks, plant breeders’ rights, industrial designs and integrated circuit  topographies. 
Governance 
The NRC is a departmental agency of the Government of Canada, reporting to  Parliament through the Minister of Innovation, S
ovation, Science and Economic Development. It is  governed by a council of appointees drawn from its client community (comprising the  Chair, the President, and up to ten other members).
